[Amit Varma]: during this period of time.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.880
[Amit Varma]: So now, you know, because I hardly know you at all, I just know you from your very scientific

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:12.760
[Amit Varma]: crisp factual tweets, I want to get to know a little more.

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:16.760
[Amit Varma]: So tell me, tell me, you know, a bit about your childhood, where did you grow up?

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:17.760
[Guest]: What was that like?

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:18.760
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:22.160
[Guest]: Okay, so where to start?

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:27.640
[Guest]: I was, my parents were both physicians.

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:31.800
[Guest]: I say were because my father passed away six years ago.

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:39.480
[Guest]: And my father came from a very small village at the Bengal-Odisha border, and when we say

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:45.440
[Guest]: to our children that we had to walk in the snow or so far to actually get to a school,

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:51.040
[Guest]: in my father's case, he did have to walk from his village to get to his school.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:55.560
[Guest]: And from there, from that remote village where there was no electricity, there was no running

00:06:55.560 --> 00:07:02.160
[Guest]: water, he went to medical college, and then from there to he did his post graduation,

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:07.000
[Guest]: he did his MD from Chandigarh, and then his DM from Ames.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.080
[Guest]: My mother went to Calcutta Medical College.

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:14.520
[Guest]: And she from there, she also went to Ames, and they were both doctors there.

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:17.620
[Guest]: So I was born at Ames in New Delhi.

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:22.200
[Guest]: And after that, my father was in the United States by both my parents were in the US for

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:23.200
[Guest]: some time.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:27.360
[Guest]: So I went to school there for a little bit, and I came back to India.

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:32.120
[Guest]: And then my formative years were actually mostly in India.

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:37.160
[Guest]: So I when I came back to India, I learned to read and write in Bangla, I learned to

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:41.340
[Guest]: play cricket at a much later age than a lot of other people.

00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:45.600
[Guest]: And I went through school and then both my parents were like, okay, so we're doctors,

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:51.500
[Guest]: it's basically almost inevitable that you will have to be a physician.

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:57.680
[Guest]: But I figured out a little bit later on when I was with my father and sometimes even at

00:07:57.680 --> 00:08:02.920
[Guest]: night because he when he moved back, he moved back to a small tertiary district town and

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:07.960
[Guest]: there weren't that many was a US trained board certified cardiologist and there weren't that

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:10.260
[Guest]: many physicians there at that time.

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:15.680
[Guest]: And so in the middle of the night, sometimes I would have to go with him with the ECG machine

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:18.280
[Guest]: and help him with that.

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:23.320
[Guest]: And I realized at that time that I was more into the research side of it, I wasn't going

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:27.800
[Guest]: to be a very good clinician, I just did not have that in me.

00:08:27.800 --> 00:08:32.160
[Guest]: And the other thing I realized is I really loved biology.

00:08:32.160 --> 00:08:38.760
[Guest]: And one of the things is that if you look into any life form on the planet right now,

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:43.080
[Guest]: because it's had 4 billion years of evolution, there are some remarkable things about it,

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:46.440
[Guest]: we just have to keep looking and be curious about it.

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:50.960
[Guest]: So I did my bachelor's degree and my master's degree in India.

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:58.680
[Guest]: And I got a very nice fellowship, a university fellowship to study microbiology at the Ohio

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:02.180
[Guest]: State University in the US.

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:04.720
[Guest]: And I came over to the US.

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:09.480
[Guest]: And I remember one of the first courses I took in the US.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:11.600
[Guest]: And I absolutely bombed it.

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:14.600
[Guest]: And that's because I didn't know how to learn anything.

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:20.040
[Guest]: I had gone through the Indian system of basically picking up a lot of facts and trying to crack

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:21.600
[Guest]: exams.

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:26.760
[Guest]: And so when I was taking this course, this was in the first semester, first quarter of

00:09:26.760 --> 00:09:31.840
[Guest]: my PhD, and the professors, each professor was coming in, and they would just be presenting

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:36.160
[Guest]: a few papers of research relevant to their own work.

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:38.720
[Guest]: I picked up all the facts in those papers.

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:44.260
[Guest]: But when the exam actually came, they didn't ask any other facts, they wanted me to synthesize

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:50.200
[Guest]: what was in those papers to be able to come up with completely independent and open-ended

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:56.400
[Guest]: answers to questions that they had that were tangentially related to those papers.

00:09:56.400 --> 00:09:59.240
[Guest]: And I really did poorly in that first exam.

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:03.800
[Guest]: But after that, I figured out that this is how I was, and this is what I was thinking

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:09.960
[Guest]: all along is that I was always sort of a rebellious person who asked like, the how and the why.

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:13.400
[Guest]: And this and so then I took like a duck to water after that.

00:10:13.400 --> 00:10:20.840
[Guest]: And I did better after that, I was very fortunate to be able to get into a lab at the time that

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:23.880
[Guest]: they were doing really groundbreaking work.

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:31.480
[Guest]: So the lab that I joined at Ohio State University, to do my PhD, they had at that time discovered

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:33.220
[Guest]: a new amino acid.

00:10:33.220 --> 00:10:38.920
[Guest]: So typically, as as most even high school students will be able to tell you, folks who

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:43.640
[Guest]: take biology that there are 20 amino acids that are inserted into proteins, and these

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:46.480
[Guest]: are coded in the genetic code.

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:53.960
[Guest]: There are a few cases of a 21st amino acid, which had been discovered in 1986.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:11:00.400
[Guest]: When I joined the lab in 2001, the lab I joined, they had to back to back, well, they had two

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:08.340
[Guest]: science papers demonstrating the genetic encoding of the 22nd amino acid pyrolysine.

00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:12.120
[Guest]: And this was basically something that went into the textbooks, and it was discovered

00:11:12.120 --> 00:11:16.760
[Guest]: as being equivalent of discovering a new particle in physics.

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:18.400
[Guest]: And that sort of appealed to me.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:24.200
[Guest]: And that has sort of been my driving interest in science, is that it is not static.

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:30.200
[Guest]: All along, we have been reading these textbooks that everything is as it has been, nothing

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:34.740
[Guest]: ever changes in science, the textbooks, the editions get updated, and we just memorize

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:36.120
[Guest]: those facts.

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:38.720
[Guest]: But there was a great time to be in that lab.

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:45.520
[Guest]: And I joined that lab, I had some very amazing friends that I worked with in that lab, got

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:48.720
[Guest]: a really great and challenging project.

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:53.400
[Guest]: And the first paper, when we were getting it done, it was basically elucidating the

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:58.920
[Guest]: process by which that amino acid gets inserted into specific proteins.

00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:03.960
[Guest]: And we did all the experiments, we knew there was another group working on it as well.

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:08.320
[Guest]: And we sent it into science as well, because the earlier papers had been in science.

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:09.600
[Guest]: And they rejected the paper.

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:14.400
[Guest]: They said, they gave us a very short amount of time and said the paper is, it looks good,

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:19.440
[Guest]: but it's basically they sent us a standard of form rejection letter.

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:23.720
[Guest]: And so we send it around in nature, we're saying we're not going to try anywhere else,

00:12:23.720 --> 00:12:29.000
[Guest]: we have confidence in our work, we're going to stay up to the high standard of the work

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.240
[Guest]: that we've done.

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:37.440
[Guest]: And fortunately, they asked us to do a little bit more, we did a few additional experiments,

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:39.120
[Guest]: but nature published it.

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:44.840
[Guest]: And the funny thing is after when nature published that paper, science did a write up on that

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:47.920
[Guest]: same paper that we had published.

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:51.120
[Guest]: So that was a really great opportunity for me.

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:57.960
[Guest]: And that discovery that we made has some real world applications as well.

00:12:57.960 --> 00:13:04.840
[Guest]: Scientists are using it, using that system as a tool to insert new amino acids with different

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:10.920
[Guest]: structure and function as building blocks to increase the functional capability of different

00:13:10.920 --> 00:13:13.080
[Guest]: proteins right now.

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:17.360
[Guest]: And so after that, I had a few more really good papers.

00:13:17.360 --> 00:13:22.360
[Guest]: And then when the time came around to complete my PhD, I was like, okay, I'm going to go

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:26.040
[Guest]: the traditional route, I'm going to be a scientist.

00:13:26.040 --> 00:13:32.400
[Guest]: And I had a couple of very nice postdoc interviews done, I was ready to do a postdoc.

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:40.640
[Guest]: And then all of a sudden, I saw this, this job ad for an assistant managing editor position

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:47.840
[Guest]: for a newish scientific journal in the field of chemical biology, which is using the tools

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:53.240
[Guest]: of chemistry and biochemistry to solve important problems in biology.

00:13:53.240 --> 00:13:58.200
[Guest]: And I looked at the job ad and it said, okay, at that time, it was like, I would be looking

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:03.080
[Guest]: at all the manuscripts that would be coming into the journal, working with the scientific

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:09.620
[Guest]: editors and deciding whether those manuscripts should go out to peer review, I would be writing

00:14:09.620 --> 00:14:16.540
[Guest]: summaries of papers, I would be going to meetings and commissioning work.

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:23.600
[Guest]: And then we were also doing podcasts at that time, interviews with authors in the, well,

00:14:23.600 --> 00:14:27.800
[Guest]: I say we, so what happened is I ultimately did apply for it.

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:33.280
[Guest]: And I did get the job and I joined there, that's a little over a decade ago.

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:39.480
[Guest]: And that was a very thrilling and intellectually rewarding experience for me there.

00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:45.840
[Guest]: As I started on working on a newish journal, a journal that is now fairly well known and

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:55.640
[Guest]: established and working with editors who were scientifically amazing and at the top of their

00:14:55.640 --> 00:15:02.080
[Guest]: individual disciplines, but were also very, very kind to this kid who had just come out

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:04.440
[Guest]: of a lab and basically heard him out.

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:07.040
[Guest]: So I do consider them my mentors.

00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:12.640
[Guest]: And so at that time I was working with some of my editors were Laura Kiesling, who's at

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:16.880
[Guest]: MIT and is one of the leaders in chemical biology.

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:22.080
[Guest]: Jennifer Doudna was one of the editors I worked with at that time, and she won the Nobel prize

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:25.380
[Guest]: last year for her CRISPR-Cas system.

00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:28.240
[Guest]: She hadn't discovered CRISPR-Cas when I had joined.

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:36.360
[Guest]: So I was actually, I know the history of that discovery and how that has moved on for genome

00:15:36.360 --> 00:15:40.160
[Guest]: editing and the potential that that definitely has.

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:46.160
[Guest]: And so when I was working on that one journal, I got involved in launching other journals.

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:52.040
[Guest]: And the way that came about is like, basically my organization said, you have all these ideas

00:15:52.040 --> 00:15:56.560
[Guest]: and we're looking to expand into new areas of science.

00:15:56.560 --> 00:15:58.280
[Guest]: Tell us about some of these ideas.

00:15:58.280 --> 00:16:03.440
[Guest]: And my first idea was we are looking at like multidisciplinary areas where we can bring

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:07.600
[Guest]: together different scientists from different fields.

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:11.100
[Guest]: And neuroscience is definitely one of the next frontiers.

00:16:11.100 --> 00:16:18.520
[Guest]: And so I, a little over a decade ago now, I helped propose, write up and launch a neuroscience

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:23.280
[Guest]: journal that brought in some of the biology and the chemistry.

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:27.720
[Guest]: And incidentally, I want to mention this because we were talking about COVID-19.

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:35.480
[Guest]: One of the first descriptions or one of the first ideas of the loss of smell after COVID-19

00:16:35.480 --> 00:16:40.080
[Guest]: was proposed by a couple of scientists based out of Pakistan who had written this perspective

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:42.280
[Guest]: in a journal that I had launched.

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:45.860
[Guest]: So I was very, very thrilled by that.

00:16:45.860 --> 00:16:51.500
[Guest]: And this happened early on, I think around February or March of 2020.

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:54.720
[Guest]: And so after that, I haven't looked back.

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:57.480
[Guest]: I have been involved in launching other journals as well.

00:16:57.480 --> 00:17:00.400
[Guest]: I've launched a synthetic biology journal.

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:06.400
[Guest]: So synthetic biology is basically using the tools and techniques of, of engineering to

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:12.560
[Guest]: biology and using cells as factories to produce products.

00:17:12.560 --> 00:17:16.280
[Guest]: So it's the, it's the next step of biotechnology.

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:19.640
[Guest]: So I would say it's biotechnology 2.0 or 3.0.

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:22.120
[Guest]: And so I helped launch that journal.

00:17:22.120 --> 00:17:24.480
[Guest]: I launched an infectious diseases journal.

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:26.160
[Guest]: This was before the pandemic.

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:32.240
[Guest]: And then I've moved on to other areas now where the portfolio of journals that I work

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:40.840
[Guest]: with include climate change, sustainable chemistry, energy, and material science, physical chemistry,

00:17:40.840 --> 00:17:41.840
[Guest]: photonics.

00:17:41.840 --> 00:17:43.040
[Guest]: So I've moved.

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:49.520
[Guest]: So one of the reasons I left the bench is because I was sort of very, very skilled and

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:54.440
[Guest]: I knew a lot about one very specific area of science and I wanted to become more of

00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:55.440
[Guest]: a generalist.

00:17:55.440 --> 00:17:58.560
[Guest]: And I think that that happened over, over time.

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:03.800
[Guest]: As you mentioned, most people on Twitter don't know anything, any of this, because I kept

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:10.320
[Guest]: us very, very low profile and I didn't mix what I did at work with my tweets, which were

00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:18.080
[Guest]: sometimes just philosophical musings and sometimes my travel and, and, and my experiments and

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:19.880
[Guest]: failed experiments in the kitchen.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:20.880
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:24.960
[Amit Varma]: So there is so much to unpack there and so many strands and thank God I have a notebook.

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:28.520
[Amit Varma]: So I'm kind of taking notes of all the things I want to talk about.

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:33.280
[Amit Varma]: But the first thing that kind of intrigued me was the love for biology, because I don't

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:36.560
[Amit Varma]: come across too many people who say that they love biology as a kid.

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:40.480
[Amit Varma]: And this is obviously a function of the way that it's taught to us and all of that.

00:18:40.480 --> 00:18:43.720
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps, you know, your parents being doctors might have helped and all of that.

00:18:43.720 --> 00:18:50.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of my sort of big complaints about our education system, not just here,

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:55.200
[Amit Varma]: but I think kind of everywhere is that, you know, many of the things we are taught, in

00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:58.640
[Amit Varma]: fact, everything we are taught is potentially full of wonder.

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:03.760
[Amit Varma]: Like I think about this most in the context of mathematics, that it's taught in such boring,

00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:06.800
[Amit Varma]: dull ways and people just turn away from it.

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:12.720
[Amit Varma]: But actually, it's like so integral to our lives and explain so much and it's not even,

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:13.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, difficult.

00:19:13.720 --> 00:19:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And I can see sort of a similar process with biology and I was sort of intrigued when you

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:23.040
[Amit Varma]: said that when you kind of took the first exam and that you as because you were in that

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:26.880
[Amit Varma]: rote learning kind of frame of mind, it didn't quite work out.

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Some sort of wondering that, you know, this whole way of thinking like, like these days,

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:36.020
[Amit Varma]: whenever I learn something new, I just first try to go back to first principles.

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:39.360
[Amit Varma]: So in the sense, don't tell me the right way of doing anything, don't tell me the process

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:43.040
[Amit Varma]: by which one does something, I want to go back to first principles, think of it from

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:44.040
[Amit Varma]: there.

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:45.720
[Amit Varma]: And then I can work a lot of the stuff out.

00:19:45.720 --> 00:19:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And then whatever I subsequently learn is kind of easy to understand.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:55.440
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me that when I meet other people with this kind of approach, it strikes

00:19:55.440 --> 00:19:58.080
[Amit Varma]: me that you can apply it to everything, right?

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:04.320
[Amit Varma]: And you've kind of spoken about how, you know, you begin in biology, but then you kind of

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:07.920
[Amit Varma]: spread out like this, you spoke about synthetic biology, where you're applying the principles

00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:12.480
[Amit Varma]: of engineering to biology, which is fascinating to me, and you're bringing this other prism.

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:16.620
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that there is, you know, a certain kind of person who does this, who'll,

00:20:16.620 --> 00:20:20.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, look at the first principles of everything, who'll, you know, and therefore

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:24.920
[Amit Varma]: for them, it's easy not to get trapped in the conventions of a particular field, but

00:20:24.920 --> 00:20:29.680
[Amit Varma]: to go beyond and to, you know, apply other prisms, apply other methods, and it kind of

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:30.840
[Amit Varma]: broadens your thinking.

00:20:30.840 --> 00:20:36.280
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me that many people, even many accomplished people sort of get trapped

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:39.040
[Amit Varma]: by the conventions of their sort of field.

00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:44.720
[Amit Varma]: So now that you've taken this interesting journey, whereby the nature of your work starting

00:20:44.720 --> 00:20:50.160
[Amit Varma]: journals in all these different fields, you are constantly one interacting with all of

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:56.040
[Amit Varma]: these people, and to also sort of expanding your own knowledge and all of that, what sort

00:20:56.040 --> 00:21:01.960
[Amit Varma]: of your sense of the ecosystem out there, like, are there many thinkers like you or

00:21:01.960 --> 00:21:03.360
[Amit Varma]: is it kind of an exception?

00:21:03.360 --> 00:21:08.520
[Amit Varma]: Do you wish there were more people who took a broader view of the science and at the same

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:11.840
[Amit Varma]: time, a deeper view than, you know, might be the case?

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:15.800
[Amit Varma]: Because I certainly see that, you know, in fields that I know a little bit about, like

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:20.240
[Amit Varma]: economics or whatever, that there will be people who are, you know, extremely accomplished,

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:25.400
[Amit Varma]: but they're almost functioning within the bounds of what they have learned in an academic

00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:26.400
[Amit Varma]: sense.

00:21:26.400 --> 00:21:29.840
[Amit Varma]: And they're not just looking at the world around them and, you know, applying those

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:35.240
[Amit Varma]: principles to everything or taking insight from, you know, other methods.

00:21:35.240 --> 00:21:40.240
[Guest]: I think there are a lot of people who think like this, and I fervently believe that all

00:21:40.240 --> 00:21:48.720
[Guest]: children grow up like this, that when they are very young, maybe before they have it

00:21:48.720 --> 00:21:53.800
[Guest]: beaten out of them in school by teachers who say that this is the way that you have to

00:21:53.800 --> 00:22:00.200
[Guest]: do something, or do you know more than me, or you have to get good marks in an exam.

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:06.000
[Guest]: I think even, and I really enjoy interacting with very young children.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:12.340
[Guest]: They ask some of the best questions, they do not have the same language.

00:22:12.340 --> 00:22:17.560
[Guest]: So you have to start from what you said, first principles, you cannot assume that they will

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:19.300
[Guest]: understand the jargon.

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:26.600
[Guest]: They do not take anything for granted, or they won't, I mean, it's a simple question

00:22:26.600 --> 00:22:32.320
[Guest]: of even asking, looking outside and saying, like, where did the moon come from?

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:34.140
[Guest]: And we see it so often.

00:22:34.140 --> 00:22:39.840
[Guest]: But it's not a question and it's not a question that we should discard or, or why does time

00:22:39.840 --> 00:22:44.280
[Guest]: move in one direction is the things that after a certain amount of time, we start to take

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:45.280
[Guest]: for granted.

00:22:45.280 --> 00:22:49.000
[Guest]: But I think all children have that sense of awe in that wonder.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:50.000
[Guest]: And I agree with you.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:57.440
[Guest]: I think children take to the basics of mathematics very, very early on, and then somehow because

00:22:57.440 --> 00:23:03.840
[Guest]: of the process of which it is taught that and, and some children are told that they

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:10.160
[Guest]: are not good at it, and they have to do it a certain way that it just, it just gets lost

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:13.200
[Guest]: and it just gets beaten out of them.

00:23:13.200 --> 00:23:19.360
[Guest]: But overall, I think that was one of the reasons why I wanted to write this book.

00:23:19.360 --> 00:23:24.760
[Guest]: And for me, that was one of the challenges of writing this book is, and writing for the

00:23:24.760 --> 00:23:30.920
[Guest]: public was, I will say, after having written perspectives, and editorials and papers for

00:23:30.920 --> 00:23:37.040
[Guest]: scientists, it was much harder because there is no common language, I cannot use the language,

00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:43.800
[Guest]: the terse, precise way of writing that goes into a paper and assume that the reader will

00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:45.160
[Guest]: be able to understand it.

00:23:45.160 --> 00:23:52.760
[Guest]: And so starting from first principle, and trying to develop a core set of ideas, was

00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:57.360
[Guest]: at least for me, one of the driving principles for for writing this book.

00:23:57.360 --> 00:24:03.640
[Guest]: But as people get into their own disciplines, I have also noticed this, this is also true

00:24:03.640 --> 00:24:11.560
[Guest]: of the various disciplines of biology or chemistry, they do not, there is very little crosstalk.

00:24:11.560 --> 00:24:16.560
[Guest]: And we do see it in in some other disciplines.

00:24:16.560 --> 00:24:22.840
[Guest]: And I think we did see a little bit of it during the pandemic with many people from

00:24:22.840 --> 00:24:25.280
[Guest]: various disciplines coming together.

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:28.280
[Guest]: But even then, that's not always the case.

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:34.480
[Guest]: We had, just to give you one very, very relevant example with these variants, you know, the

00:24:34.480 --> 00:24:38.680
[Guest]: first variant that came out of the UK was B.1.1.7.

00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest]: And at that point, when that first variant came out, the virologists are the people who

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:50.080
[Guest]: are looking at the viruses and at sort of a virus level and molecular level and at an

00:24:50.080 --> 00:24:52.080
[Guest]: infectious level.

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:56.560
[Guest]: The epidemiologists are looking at the spread and the trajectory of spread.

00:24:56.560 --> 00:25:00.320
[Guest]: The virologists were saying, okay, mutations happen all the time.

00:25:00.320 --> 00:25:07.240
[Guest]: Therefore, we do not think that this, this mutation is anything different, or that it

00:25:07.240 --> 00:25:08.240
[Guest]: spreads more.

00:25:08.240 --> 00:25:13.880
[Guest]: We have to show us in an animal model that this is, this is spreading more rapidly.

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:19.880
[Guest]: And some virologists that I respect a lot, and have actually written textbooks at that

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:25.960
[Guest]: point in early January, were not believing that this was a more infectious strain or

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:28.000
[Guest]: variant of the virus.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:34.040
[Guest]: However, epidemiologists who have their own way of looking at data, and they were finding

00:25:34.040 --> 00:25:39.920
[Guest]: in the UK that this virus was actually now becoming more prevalent than the original

00:25:39.920 --> 00:25:46.840
[Guest]: strain, the lineage from Wuhan and the other mutant that was there, the B614G mutant, which

00:25:46.840 --> 00:25:48.780
[Guest]: was predominant at the time.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:55.240
[Guest]: And so that was sort of a different line of research, no less relevant, but it's just

00:25:55.240 --> 00:26:00.840
[Guest]: because of the individual aspects of disciplines that they were not talking to each other.

00:26:00.840 --> 00:26:07.080
[Guest]: And I think we'll see more examples of this across all the disciplines, not just biology

00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:10.440
[Guest]: or physics, but even, even economics.

00:26:10.440 --> 00:26:17.440
[Guest]: My former advisor used to say that if you need to build something, if you need a stool,

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:19.900
[Guest]: a stool has to have three legs.

00:26:19.900 --> 00:26:25.080
[Guest]: So you need three, for any major discovery, you have to have at least three independent

00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:32.520
[Guest]: ways of corroborating that idea or thought, especially if it is a paradigm shift.

00:26:32.520 --> 00:26:41.520
[Guest]: And so what often happens is that when we don't get these different aspects, or these

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:48.360
[Guest]: different groups working together, we don't see the same outcomes.

00:26:48.360 --> 00:26:49.360
[Amit Varma]: That's so fascinating.

00:26:49.360 --> 00:26:53.480
[Amit Varma]: And what you said about, you know, the virologists here and the epidemiologists there reminds

00:26:53.480 --> 00:26:56.920
[Amit Varma]: me of, you know, your first chapter where you speak about the parable of the elephant,

00:26:56.920 --> 00:27:00.880
[Amit Varma]: that you know, that old parable, different blind men touch different parts of an elephant

00:27:00.880 --> 00:27:02.080
[Amit Varma]: and they see something different.

00:27:02.080 --> 00:27:06.400
[Amit Varma]: And of course, your point in the chapter was about the virus in general, and so many different

00:27:06.400 --> 00:27:12.000
[Amit Varma]: aspects of this pandemic, but that, you know, seems to be a little there in science also.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:17.160
[Amit Varma]: Now, sort of three conceptual questions, not conceptual, but three questions around, you

00:27:17.160 --> 00:27:18.520
[Amit Varma]: know, different themes.

00:27:18.520 --> 00:27:23.480
[Amit Varma]: And the first of them is this, like, when I teach this writing course that I teach,

00:27:23.480 --> 00:27:29.040
[Amit Varma]: I often get questions about academic writing, from people who are doing PhDs, or who have

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:30.800
[Amit Varma]: done PhDs and all of that.

00:27:30.800 --> 00:27:35.800
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, because so much of what I talk about the importance of clarity in writing

00:27:35.800 --> 00:27:40.040
[Amit Varma]: and all that almost goes very counter to the kind of conventions that exist.

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:44.760
[Amit Varma]: And I point them to this great essay by Agnes Gallard, who, by the way, is a force on Twitter,

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:46.320
[Amit Varma]: I just love her account.

00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:52.320
[Amit Varma]: And Gallard had this fine essay, I think about three months ago, four months ago, about why

00:27:52.320 --> 00:27:54.640
[Amit Varma]: academic writing is so turgid.

00:27:54.640 --> 00:28:00.200
[Amit Varma]: And her point there was that, look, someone's completed a PhD, they are on the sort of tenure

00:28:00.200 --> 00:28:04.920
[Amit Varma]: track, what do you need to get tenure, you need to publish specific number of papers

00:28:04.920 --> 00:28:09.080
[Amit Varma]: in these specific journals, and all those journals have their own conventions, their

00:28:09.080 --> 00:28:12.520
[Amit Varma]: own insider lingo, their own ways of writing.

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:17.320
[Amit Varma]: So you're optimizing for that, you're not optimizing for, say, a larger audience to

00:28:17.320 --> 00:28:20.760
[Amit Varma]: get read more widely and all of that.

00:28:20.760 --> 00:28:24.080
[Amit Varma]: And then that language seeps into everything else you do, maybe including letters to your

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:28.880
[Amit Varma]: family or whatever, though I would hope not, and you stop thinking about it.

00:28:28.880 --> 00:28:34.240
[Amit Varma]: And I was chatting about this with another friend, Ruben Abraham recently, who told me

00:28:34.240 --> 00:28:40.080
[Amit Varma]: about how, you know, this might be true for the social sciences, but in science, per se,

00:28:40.080 --> 00:28:44.840
[Amit Varma]: the papers tend to be very well written, eight to 12 pages, because they're very crisp, and

00:28:44.840 --> 00:28:45.840
[Amit Varma]: they know what they're doing.

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:48.400
[Amit Varma]: And they go from point A to point B, and all of that.

00:28:48.400 --> 00:28:49.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of more systematic.

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:53.560
[Amit Varma]: So he gave me a sort of a counter view to this saying that, look, a lot of academic

00:28:53.560 --> 00:28:55.640
[Amit Varma]: writing is turgid.

00:28:55.640 --> 00:28:59.200
[Amit Varma]: But there is a lot of joy in just reading a lot of science papers, because they kind

00:28:59.200 --> 00:29:00.520
[Amit Varma]: of bug the trend.

00:29:00.520 --> 00:29:08.080
[Amit Varma]: So now as someone who started off on that academic path, who wrote a paper, which got,

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:10.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, published in Nature and written about by here.

00:29:10.880 --> 00:29:14.680
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sort of outlook on all of this?

00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:19.180
[Amit Varma]: Like you have also therefore been an editor, you have received a lot of this turgid writing,

00:29:19.180 --> 00:29:25.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, is it incredibly commonplace, and therefore a problem, when you sort of suggest

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:30.040
[Amit Varma]: recommendations about, you know, what changes a writer should make or how they should work

00:29:30.040 --> 00:29:31.040
[Amit Varma]: on their paper?

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:34.920
[Amit Varma]: Do you also talk about the writing or do you just talk about the science and obviously,

00:29:34.920 --> 00:29:38.560
[Amit Varma]: the science is more important because the content matters, but you also talk about the

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:40.600
[Amit Varma]: writing, is that an imperative?

00:29:40.600 --> 00:29:45.560
[Amit Varma]: Are these journals sort of, like I understand that they will have specialized audiences,

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:50.940
[Amit Varma]: but would you also like to at least make them readable by the general public at large?

00:29:50.940 --> 00:29:54.720
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sort of just kind of thinking aloud, because you seem to be the perfect person

00:29:54.720 --> 00:30:00.160
[Amit Varma]: at the intersection of all of this, as both an academic, a writer, an editor, a thinker,

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:02.800
[Amit Varma]: and you know, how do you look at this space?

00:30:02.800 --> 00:30:05.960
[Guest]: Yeah, I can definitely provide my own perspective.

00:30:05.960 --> 00:30:11.680
[Guest]: And having worked on a number of a few dozen journals and having launched 10 scientific

00:30:11.680 --> 00:30:18.120
[Guest]: journals myself, I am regularly reading papers, sometimes I tweet about them as well, I read

00:30:18.120 --> 00:30:26.080
[Guest]: the papers in energy, material science, microbiology, chemistry, medicine, engineering, various

00:30:26.080 --> 00:30:27.080
[Guest]: fields.

00:30:27.080 --> 00:30:32.880
[Guest]: And it's not that I understand all of them, but I have developed a sense of getting at

00:30:32.880 --> 00:30:35.880
[Guest]: the gist very easily.

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:41.120
[Guest]: And in new fields, what I do is I usually try to do some background reading.

00:30:41.120 --> 00:30:47.080
[Guest]: And so some of the reviews are written in a different manner than some of the scientific

00:30:47.080 --> 00:30:48.080
[Guest]: papers.

00:30:48.080 --> 00:30:55.320
[Guest]: And that's because the review is more a very large perspective of the field as well.

00:30:55.320 --> 00:31:01.280
[Guest]: But a really good paper will tell you more than what the authors have actually written.

00:31:01.280 --> 00:31:09.360
[Guest]: It's very terse and turgid, as you say, but you will be able to from that paper, understand

00:31:09.360 --> 00:31:15.880
[Guest]: what the background is, what the what the reason is, why they actually did the work,

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:22.020
[Guest]: you will be able to figure out what else has been done and who else is doing that.

00:31:22.020 --> 00:31:27.560
[Guest]: You will be able to figure out what experiments they did and what those experiments show.

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:32.920
[Guest]: And you will be able to figure out what the next steps are and and what others are doing.

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:38.800
[Guest]: But a scientific paper typically is not read in the same way that something else will be

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:43.240
[Guest]: read where you, you read the abstract, then you read all the way through.

00:31:43.240 --> 00:31:48.120
[Guest]: The way that I usually read scientific paper is I read the abstract, then I look at the

00:31:48.120 --> 00:31:54.440
[Guest]: figures, then I look at the discussion at the end, then I go back and it's sort of it's

00:31:54.440 --> 00:32:00.960
[Guest]: almost like it's almost like going like hypertext, because if I see something, then I look at

00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:06.000
[Guest]: a reference, then I'll go down this rabbit hole of maybe even an hour following a certain

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.720
[Guest]: reference down that way.

00:32:08.720 --> 00:32:10.720
[Guest]: But you are absolutely right.

00:32:10.720 --> 00:32:16.200
[Guest]: Titles matter, especially in this age of even of search engines, where people are finding

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:22.240
[Guest]: a lot of research from from titles of articles, the titles really, really matter.

00:32:22.240 --> 00:32:27.400
[Guest]: The abstract has to be very succinct and has to say what has been done.

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:32.520
[Guest]: Lot of journals are now doing what are known as lay summaries, which show the which demonstrate

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:35.440
[Guest]: the significance for a broader audience.

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:37.560
[Guest]: And I am very much in favor of these.

00:32:37.560 --> 00:32:44.780
[Guest]: So when I started off as a scientific editor, one of my jobs was to write these two paragraph

00:32:44.780 --> 00:32:49.920
[Guest]: in this issue summaries for drug discovery and biology papers.

00:32:49.920 --> 00:32:53.860
[Guest]: And so I was going through them and writing those up.

00:32:53.860 --> 00:32:58.900
[Guest]: And we even asked a lot of authors to submit that with their submissions as well.

00:32:58.900 --> 00:33:02.960
[Guest]: There are other journals that do this, definitely.

00:33:02.960 --> 00:33:08.760
[Guest]: I think one of the reasons there is good science writing and there is bad science writing,

00:33:08.760 --> 00:33:09.880
[Guest]: undoubtedly.

00:33:09.880 --> 00:33:16.560
[Guest]: One of the reasons that science is written in this sort of peculiar way is that it is

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:24.040
[Guest]: very important to be accurate as opposed to be definitive in your pronouncements.

00:33:24.040 --> 00:33:29.840
[Guest]: You have to say what you're saying, but you also have to say these are the limitations.

00:33:29.840 --> 00:33:34.600
[Guest]: And that doesn't always make for a compelling read.

00:33:34.600 --> 00:33:40.040
[Guest]: And I think a lot of people who peddle in misinformation, and I've noticed this, they

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:44.400
[Guest]: have an easier time because they don't need nuance, right?

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:49.120
[Guest]: They don't need to say that this is this particular case under these conditions.

00:33:49.120 --> 00:33:53.160
[Guest]: And this is the setting and this is how much immunity you have.

00:33:53.160 --> 00:33:56.160
[Guest]: But look at this, immunity is not just the antibodies.

00:33:56.160 --> 00:34:01.560
[Guest]: You have all these other parts of the cells and you have T cells and these other components.

00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:05.580
[Guest]: They can just say, well, drink my concoction and you'll never get coronavirus.

00:34:05.580 --> 00:34:12.040
[Guest]: And those things are the ones that has no nuance and it's sort of seductive in a way

00:34:12.040 --> 00:34:16.920
[Guest]: in that they're very, I look at these WhatsApp forwards, they're actually, people should

00:34:16.920 --> 00:34:22.740
[Guest]: be doing research on them because they are very simple in what they're trying to demonstrate.

00:34:22.740 --> 00:34:26.280
[Guest]: And this completely the antithesis of what you're saying.

00:34:26.280 --> 00:34:30.960
[Guest]: But at some point, scientists do have to become science communicators.

00:34:30.960 --> 00:34:35.720
[Guest]: They have to be able to, because scientists are a part of society.

00:34:35.720 --> 00:34:41.800
[Guest]: The problem is that there really is no incentive for a scientist.

00:34:41.800 --> 00:34:47.760
[Guest]: The reward structures in science are created in such a way that scientists are always talking

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:49.840
[Guest]: to other scientists.

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:54.720
[Guest]: They are talking to administrators, they are trying to get grants.

00:34:54.720 --> 00:35:02.080
[Guest]: So by writing, for example, a popular science book, there is, a scientist is not going to

00:35:02.080 --> 00:35:06.360
[Guest]: get tenure, is not going to get a promotion.

00:35:06.360 --> 00:35:12.480
[Guest]: So I think people that do it, do it out of a sense of compulsion and maybe they have

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:14.560
[Guest]: a little bit more free time.

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:17.040
[Guest]: But you're absolutely right.

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:23.520
[Guest]: There is a peculiar and precise way of writing in science that is almost like you have to

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:24.880
[Guest]: learn another language.

00:35:24.880 --> 00:35:29.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, the problem you've expressed is very resonant.

00:35:29.520 --> 00:35:32.880
[Amit Varma]: Because the thing is, you know, the reason these, like I'm also fascinated by all the

00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:33.880
[Amit Varma]: fake news that spreads.

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:37.880
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that they get right in terms of craft is that they keep it simple.

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:41.200
[Amit Varma]: We explain the world to ourselves by telling stories about it.

00:35:41.200 --> 00:35:43.520
[Amit Varma]: And simpler stories are far easier to process.

00:35:43.520 --> 00:35:47.120
[Amit Varma]: You don't, you know, you don't have to consider a hundred nuances and all of that.

00:35:47.120 --> 00:35:49.280
[Amit Varma]: And again, I couldn't agree with you more.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:53.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is, you know, in a different context, my friend Ajay Shah, who's a public

00:35:53.680 --> 00:36:00.040
[Amit Varma]: policy guy and a great economist is also sort of, he keeps, you know, lamenting that so

00:36:00.040 --> 00:36:05.600
[Amit Varma]: many economists are on this sort of academic treadmill, where they are pursuing a set of

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:07.440
[Amit Varma]: different incentives.

00:36:07.440 --> 00:36:11.840
[Amit Varma]: And if they, you know, if the incentives were slightly more aligned to say the public good,

00:36:11.840 --> 00:36:16.160
[Amit Varma]: which comes from, you know, communicating your ideas clearly and well, getting them

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:20.280
[Amit Varma]: out there, doing research that actually goes in those directions, rather than whatever

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:25.680
[Amit Varma]: might be fashionable in academics at the moment, perhaps the world would be a better place.

00:36:25.680 --> 00:36:31.080
[Amit Varma]: Now, the thing about that I loved about your book is that it's like, I don't want to embarrass

00:36:31.080 --> 00:36:35.400
[Amit Varma]: you with praise, but I thought it's just outstanding in terms of popular science writing, because

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:40.200
[Amit Varma]: you simplify everything so much, like not in a way of making it simplistic, but in a

00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:46.080
[Amit Varma]: way of making it easy to understand in clear language, like a schoolboy with a lot of questions

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:51.120
[Amit Varma]: could get a lot of his questions answered through this book, without having a problem

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:52.120
[Amit Varma]: with it.

00:36:52.120 --> 00:36:58.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, this process of clear writing, I want to ask you a little bit about that, you know,

00:36:58.040 --> 00:37:03.360
[Amit Varma]: a few weeks ago, Krish Ashok did an episode with me where he spoke about the pyramid of

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:07.080
[Amit Varma]: learning, like, how do you learn something the best, like somebody says something to

00:37:07.080 --> 00:37:11.000
[Amit Varma]: you, you learn it one way, you read something, you learn it at a different depth, but the

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:16.520
[Amit Varma]: deepest way of learning is to teach something. And in a sense, trying to write clearly for

00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:22.080
[Amit Varma]: a mass audience is a form of teaching. And another thing that you know, Orwell had first

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:26.560
[Amit Varma]: brought about, and I keep talking about in my writing classes, a link between clear thinking

00:37:26.560 --> 00:37:30.160
[Amit Varma]: and clear writing, and how it's a two way link, like, obviously, for a clear thinker,

00:37:30.160 --> 00:37:33.720
[Amit Varma]: you're more likely to write clearly. But if you are forcing yourself to write clearly

00:37:33.720 --> 00:37:38.560
[Amit Varma]: about a subject, then you have to force yourself to think deeply about it. Because then you

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:44.880
[Amit Varma]: cannot take cover in jargon or insider lingo, or, you know, obfuscatory abstract language,

00:37:44.880 --> 00:37:50.960
[Amit Varma]: you have to get concrete, you have to explain everything in kind of simple terms, which

00:37:50.960 --> 00:37:55.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, you've done repeatedly through the book, you know, I just noted down so many

00:37:55.320 --> 00:38:00.320
[Amit Varma]: of your quotes, like proteins being like origami, or your chapter on concepts where you've spoken

00:38:00.320 --> 00:38:05.320
[Amit Varma]: about the importance of shape, you quoted Carl Sagan, talking about apple pie, which

00:38:05.320 --> 00:38:11.480
[Amit Varma]: I'll come to. And all of this is just utterly sort of delightful. So and nobody starts off

00:38:11.480 --> 00:38:16.120
[Amit Varma]: a clear writer, right? It takes a lot of work. I mean, another thing, you know, an aside

00:38:16.120 --> 00:38:20.320
[Amit Varma]: for my listeners would be that I believe writing is one of those things which you don't need

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:26.040
[Amit Varma]: any inherent quality. Everybody can be a great writer. It's just a question of making the

00:38:26.040 --> 00:38:30.800
[Amit Varma]: effort. It's not like cricket that there's a certain hand-eye coordination that is natural

00:38:30.800 --> 00:38:36.280
[Amit Varma]: or bowlers need fast twitch muscles or whatever. Everybody can learn to be a great writer period.

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:41.960
[Amit Varma]: So and everybody starts off bad, obviously, tell me about your journey as a writer, you

00:38:41.960 --> 00:38:48.480
[Amit Varma]: know, thinking about how to make complex subjects easily understandable to a lay audience. And

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:53.440
[Amit Varma]: I feel that this must have been so much harder for you. Because in the environment that you're

00:38:53.440 --> 00:38:57.960
[Amit Varma]: in, where you're reading turgid paper after turgid paper submitted by academics and my

00:38:57.960 --> 00:39:05.680
[Amit Varma]: apologies to academics, I don't mean to say they're all like this, but relatively, certainly.

00:39:05.680 --> 00:39:10.040
[Amit Varma]: What was your journey discovering your kind of writing voice? What were your role models?

00:39:10.040 --> 00:39:12.480
[Amit Varma]: What was your journey? What was it like? Tell me a bit about that.

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:17.000
[Guest]: Well, first of all, thank you so much for the praise. It is slightly embarrassing. But

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:25.120
[Guest]: also, I have to tell you this, now that you mentioned it. One of the most puzzling but

00:39:25.120 --> 00:39:32.920
[Guest]: also in a backhanded way, rewarding messages I got was from my sister. So she's an engineer.

00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:39.160
[Guest]: And she sent me a message after she read the book. And it was like, Wow, Dada, you wrote

00:39:39.160 --> 00:39:44.080
[Guest]: a science book that's not like a science book at all. And it's sort of a backhanded way

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:51.520
[Guest]: of saying like, reminding me of all the horrible textbooks that I read. And I was like, Okay,

00:39:51.520 --> 00:39:55.480
[Guest]: she's an engineer, but I really know where she's coming from with that. And but because

00:39:55.480 --> 00:40:00.160
[Guest]: she's a sister, it cannot be sort of a direct phrase, there has to be like this, this sense

00:40:00.160 --> 00:40:06.960
[Guest]: of like, how did you even do this? I, I underestimated you. But well, thank you so much for that.

00:40:06.960 --> 00:40:12.840
[Guest]: I will say that one of the things is that basically, I did think a lot about the analogies

00:40:12.840 --> 00:40:19.640
[Guest]: to use. And, and for me, I am a little bit, I like to think, obviously, mathematically,

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:26.720
[Guest]: but I'm also a visual thinker. And sometimes breaking down these, these concepts into into

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:35.280
[Guest]: visual pieces is very, very helpful. Fortunately, obviously, I can't embed a YouTube video into

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:42.360
[Guest]: a book. But fortunately, the process of infection is such and the process of how the immune

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:50.600
[Guest]: system responds, and how disease develops. And that whole cycle is such that you can

00:40:50.600 --> 00:40:57.320
[Guest]: sit down and basically visualize it. And so that took me a while though, as you mentioned,

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:02.200
[Guest]: each individual part of that is one sentence in that book might actually be someone's science

00:41:02.200 --> 00:41:08.880
[Guest]: paper or nature paper, or even some some major observation that it took them a while to do.

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:13.320
[Guest]: But pieced together, if you just break it down, as you mentioned early on into the individual

00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:18.720
[Guest]: parts of, okay, how, first of all, starting from how big is the virus? How big is the

00:41:18.720 --> 00:41:24.060
[Guest]: cell? What does it need to do to actually get inside the body? I mean, there are millions

00:41:24.060 --> 00:41:29.920
[Guest]: of viruses and you starting back and saying, why are there only 220 viruses that infect

00:41:29.920 --> 00:41:34.480
[Guest]: the human body? I mean, we always say, okay, viruses, they're, they're harming us. But

00:41:34.480 --> 00:41:40.120
[Guest]: there, among the vast number of viruses, there are only a few. So there is something special

00:41:40.120 --> 00:41:44.960
[Guest]: about this virus compared to other viruses. And then taking it to the next step of trying

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:52.240
[Guest]: to visualize those processes, for me, at least, was very helpful. As far as right, the actual

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:58.440
[Guest]: writing process itself, you are absolutely right, it was iterative. And it was iterative

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:05.160
[Guest]: in the sense of also that the data was changing. I went through multiple drafts, this was not

00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:13.360
[Guest]: a static. This was not a static subject where I could go through a research phase and collect

00:42:13.360 --> 00:42:18.480
[Guest]: all the papers and then sit down in my room and then go through a writing phase. This

00:42:18.480 --> 00:42:25.400
[Guest]: was a project where I was doing the research and the writing simultaneously. And so I went

00:42:25.400 --> 00:42:32.840
[Guest]: through many drafts of writing this. But whenever I was reading a paper, apart from annotating

00:42:32.840 --> 00:42:40.280
[Guest]: it and marking it up, what I was also doing is I would write a summary of that paper.

00:42:40.280 --> 00:42:46.340
[Guest]: And then after I wrote that summary, I would come back to it asking myself, why would somebody

00:42:46.340 --> 00:42:51.520
[Guest]: who is not a scientist be interested in this? What would they actually get out of it that

00:42:51.520 --> 00:42:58.400
[Guest]: would be relevant to the bigger picture of SARS-CoV-2 and COVID-19? And often what would

00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:04.720
[Guest]: happen is that then that summary, which was two paragraphs, would then be condensed into

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:10.200
[Guest]: maybe two sentences. And then after that, I would start to expand that because you don't

00:43:10.200 --> 00:43:17.680
[Guest]: also want to leave them with basically without any particular context or any perspective

00:43:17.680 --> 00:43:22.120
[Guest]: of what this might mean. So I don't know how successful I was, but that was the process

00:43:22.120 --> 00:43:28.480
[Guest]: that I had to use. And then integrating it together. I also, as you probably have noticed,

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:33.140
[Guest]: when I wrote the book, I also had a framework of basically systematically deciding what

00:43:33.140 --> 00:43:38.520
[Guest]: each of these chapters would be and breaking it down into that. And that was very, very

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:45.440
[Guest]: helpful to have those specific buckets. And so that I didn't go off in a way that I would

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:50.600
[Guest]: if I had been doing another form of writing such as poetry or creative writing.

00:43:50.600 --> 00:43:53.880
[Amit Varma]: And did those buckets come at the start? Like, did you sit down at the start and first make

00:43:53.880 --> 00:43:58.800
[Amit Varma]: the structure and then say, I'll go according to the structure? Or does it kind of evolve

00:43:58.800 --> 00:44:01.160
[Guest]: as it goes along?

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:08.720
[Guest]: That evolved. I had a little bit of a sense of what I wanted to write. But when I was

00:44:08.720 --> 00:44:15.920
[Guest]: first thinking about this project, I did not know the final shape of what this book would

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:23.260
[Guest]: actually be. And I have to thank my publishers for for putting up with me and for letting

00:44:23.260 --> 00:44:30.240
[Guest]: me hand in a book that was slightly different or maybe significantly different from the

00:44:30.240 --> 00:44:32.280
[Amit Varma]: proposal that I wrote.

00:44:32.280 --> 00:44:35.720
[Amit Varma]: Another crazy thing that kind of strikes me about it is like you correctly said, everything

00:44:35.720 --> 00:44:39.680
[Amit Varma]: is changing while you're writing, right? So people often speak of journalism as the first

00:44:39.680 --> 00:44:44.760
[Amit Varma]: draft of history, which, you know, has its dangers as well. And while you're writing

00:44:44.760 --> 00:44:50.080
[Amit Varma]: this book, in a sense, it is not a definitive book of everything that the COVID-19 is about,

00:44:50.080 --> 00:44:54.160
[Amit Varma]: because we are still learning so much about it. We are in a sense, you know, in a fog

00:44:54.160 --> 00:45:00.040
[Amit Varma]: of war situation, where there are so many things that we don't know. So is that something

00:45:00.040 --> 00:45:04.440
[Amit Varma]: that kind of worried you? Or I mean, for the majority of the book, of course, you've looked

00:45:04.440 --> 00:45:09.880
[Amit Varma]: at basic concepts and first principles and just kind of explained everything from scratch.

00:45:09.880 --> 00:45:14.000
[Amit Varma]: And you've, you know, there's nothing in it that is in a sense going to be falsified,

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:21.280
[Amit Varma]: so to say, you've, you know, but it can provide a lay reader a bedrock of understanding exactly

00:45:21.280 --> 00:45:26.120
[Amit Varma]: what is going on, which is what is so good about it. But how do you how do you then in

00:45:26.120 --> 00:45:32.440
[Amit Varma]: the in the process of writing? Is there a point and this is relevant, not just to the

00:45:32.440 --> 00:45:36.160
[Amit Varma]: knowledge that you're putting in the book, but also in the in terms of crafting the writing

00:45:36.160 --> 00:45:40.520
[Amit Varma]: itself, that does there come a point where you say that, listen, I'm not totally happy,

00:45:40.520 --> 00:45:45.160
[Amit Varma]: but I have to let it go now. Because I'm guessing that, you know, complete satisfaction with

00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:50.720
[Amit Varma]: whatever is there is kind of impossible, right? So what was that like for you? Did you did

00:45:50.720 --> 00:45:54.640
[Amit Varma]: you have imposter syndrome? Did you did you think that, you know, can I do this? What

00:45:54.640 --> 00:45:55.640
[Guest]: was that like?

00:45:55.640 --> 00:46:04.680
[Guest]: So one thing I did do will say is that it is important to have this sense of epistemic

00:46:04.680 --> 00:46:11.960
[Guest]: humility that in a pandemic, you cannot know every single aspect of what is going on. And

00:46:11.960 --> 00:46:17.720
[Guest]: this is why it was a lot of work, but it was helpful to actually have references and notes

00:46:17.720 --> 00:46:24.080
[Guest]: in the back of the book where I could reference the experts and say, this particular sentence

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:30.160
[Guest]: or this particular idea, which is prevalent at the time is not an idea that I have come

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:35.600
[Guest]: up with, because I think a book, maybe if I write fiction in the future, that I will

00:46:35.600 --> 00:46:40.360
[Guest]: come up with something more imaginative, but a book on public health during a pandemic

00:46:40.360 --> 00:46:46.280
[Guest]: is not a time for significant independent theories or unsubstantiated ideas. So all

00:46:46.280 --> 00:46:51.840
[Guest]: of those chapters, I'm not an expert, I want to stress again, that I'm not an expert, I

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:59.560
[Guest]: relied on my ability to translate the science and to condense it. But all of those aspects

00:46:59.560 --> 00:47:06.720
[Guest]: are cited in the back and people can use that as a jumping off point, as you mentioned,

00:47:06.720 --> 00:47:13.520
[Guest]: after they have a sense of the broader landscape. So I did not want it to be this scientific

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:22.040
[Guest]: document or this monograph at all. As far as leaving it at a certain point, yes, there

00:47:22.040 --> 00:47:29.800
[Guest]: were aspects that obviously, I could have pursued further. And we don't have the answers

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:34.400
[Guest]: to that. One thing you will notice about the book is I've always said, this is what we

00:47:34.400 --> 00:47:40.440
[Guest]: don't know. And I've used that as to the best of my ability to say, this information is

00:47:40.440 --> 00:47:45.160
[Guest]: unknown at this point of time, it may take us six months, it may take us years to look

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:51.040
[Guest]: into this. And that varied from some very contentious issues, such as the lockdown,

00:47:51.040 --> 00:47:58.240
[Guest]: to prior immunity, to the various, the extreme heterogeneity of people who are getting very

00:47:58.240 --> 00:48:05.040
[Guest]: sick to people who are having asymptomatic infections, to long COVID, or post COVID syndrome,

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:10.840
[Guest]: which affects different people in different ways. And so I left it at that with a sense

00:48:10.840 --> 00:48:16.600
[Guest]: of being comfortable with saying that, I don't know this, nobody knows definitively at this

00:48:16.600 --> 00:48:23.800
[Guest]: time. It was a good stopping off point in that I knew about the vaccines. So I think

00:48:23.800 --> 00:48:31.600
[Guest]: this, I would have felt a little bit bad, if the book had been written, and it had come

00:48:31.600 --> 00:48:38.680
[Guest]: out before we had approved vaccines. I also knew about the UK variant and that it was

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:44.580
[Guest]: more infectious. I had not foreseen or didn't know about the other variants. And perhaps

00:48:44.580 --> 00:48:51.160
[Guest]: that can be sort of an additional appendix, or a 23rd chapter. But I did know that the

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:57.080
[Guest]: variant was coming and that it had been shown that it was more infectious. So at that point,

00:48:57.080 --> 00:49:05.640
[Guest]: I did have that sense of what was going to be happening in the next few months, at least.

00:49:05.640 --> 00:49:10.480
[Guest]: What this book has absolutely avoided is going into the daily numbers and into the daily

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:16.760
[Guest]: curves. And I did that for a number of reasons. One is that it reduces the shelf life of a

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:23.000
[Guest]: book of this nature. The second aspect of this is that it takes us away from the sense

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:28.720
[Guest]: of humility. Because even when I was writing this book, I said during the first wave, there

00:49:28.720 --> 00:49:34.060
[Guest]: were some countries that had fared well. One of them was Germany. And Germany got absolutely

00:49:34.060 --> 00:49:39.560
[Guest]: devastated during the winter because of some measures that they didn't take, but also because

00:49:39.560 --> 00:49:48.480
[Guest]: of the variant strains as well. And then I was very careful in not making any precise

00:49:48.480 --> 00:49:55.240
[Guest]: prognostications about the trajectory of the pandemic in India and what was happening.

00:49:55.240 --> 00:50:00.960
[Guest]: Because I wasn't riding the wave and I didn't want to ride the wave of saying, well, the

00:50:00.960 --> 00:50:08.240
[Guest]: cases went down because Indians have immunity. And then regretting a few months later, well,

00:50:08.240 --> 00:50:14.560
[Guest]: I was wrong here, the cases went up. And so I tried to avoid that as much as possible.

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:22.480
[Guest]: With all of that said, because I'm in a field where the shelf life of documents and of papers

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:28.280
[Guest]: is very short to begin with, this is something that we are all resigned to. I know that when

00:50:28.280 --> 00:50:33.980
[Guest]: I wrote my thesis, when I write papers, when any one of us writes anything, it is going

00:50:33.980 --> 00:50:39.600
[Guest]: to get outdated pretty soon. So we try to do our best. The book allowed me an opportunity

00:50:39.600 --> 00:50:45.080
[Guest]: to, as you pointed out, and thank you for saying that, try to bring in the broader concepts,

00:50:45.080 --> 00:50:49.220
[Guest]: which I hope will not be obsolete in the near future.

00:50:49.220 --> 00:50:54.080
[Amit Varma]: So I'll just inform our listeners at this point that this is actually being recorded

00:50:54.080 --> 00:51:01.080
[Amit Varma]: on April 13th, 2021, though it is April 12th where Anirwan is. So do consider that the

00:51:01.080 --> 00:51:05.400
[Amit Varma]: miracle that I am asking my questions on the 13th and he is answering them on the 12th,

00:51:05.400 --> 00:51:11.700
[Amit Varma]: the miracles of science, perhaps. I'm struck by this phrase that you used, epistemic humility,

00:51:11.700 --> 00:51:16.120
[Amit Varma]: because I used it in a prior episode. And then one of my guests used it in a previous

00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:20.520
[Amit Varma]: episode, in an episode after that, when we were talking about COVID, in fact, the policy

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:24.840
[Amit Varma]: responses to it. And someone wrote into me saying, hey, Amit, you say never use jargon,

00:51:24.840 --> 00:51:31.560
[Amit Varma]: why have you? But yeah, but in a sense, you know, to not to cut the jargon part of it,

00:51:31.560 --> 00:51:35.560
[Amit Varma]: you can say it's just about being humble about what you know. And that's kind of what I want

00:51:35.560 --> 00:51:42.020
[Amit Varma]: to ask you about, because it strikes me that there is, if you're achieving excellence in

00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:48.140
[Amit Varma]: anything, you know, there is this balance to be struck between having confidence in

00:51:48.140 --> 00:51:52.400
[Amit Varma]: what you are, what you know, and what you're capable of, and also having the humility to

00:51:52.400 --> 00:51:58.160
[Amit Varma]: learn more. And, you know, an example I often give is, you know, people think Virat Kohli

00:51:58.160 --> 00:52:06.160
[Amit Varma]: is like a very aggro kind of person, arrogant and full of himself. But to get to the level

00:52:06.160 --> 00:52:11.200
[Amit Varma]: where he is, he must have spent 1000s of hours in the nets focusing on what he's doing wrong.

00:52:11.200 --> 00:52:15.640
[Amit Varma]: So there is an inbuilt humility in that process. Now, in the world of science, also, it strikes

00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:19.040
[Amit Varma]: me that if you're too humble, if you think that I don't know anything, everything could

00:52:19.040 --> 00:52:24.840
[Amit Varma]: be wrong, it possibly becomes difficult to proceed. So you have to have a certain amount

00:52:24.840 --> 00:52:30.680
[Amit Varma]: of belief in your knowledge and the value of the work you are doing, and so on and so

00:52:30.680 --> 00:52:35.600
[Amit Varma]: forth. But at the same time, there also has to be a certain amount of humility, like what

00:52:35.600 --> 00:52:40.960
[Amit Varma]: you pointed out in the clash between or the argument between the virologists and the epidemiologists.

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:45.880
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, there has to be that humility and that openness. And you can't just sit

00:52:45.880 --> 00:52:51.480
[Amit Varma]: back and say that, no, this is my field, who are these other lay people to, you know, comment

00:52:51.480 --> 00:52:55.720
[Amit Varma]: on it and, you know, make Twitter threads about something that they haven't actually

00:52:55.720 --> 00:53:04.760
[Amit Varma]: received training in. So, given that you are someone who's obviously, due to the work due

00:53:04.760 --> 00:53:09.640
[Amit Varma]: to being an editor, due to being a science writer, or, you know, that's inbuilt in you.

00:53:09.640 --> 00:53:12.680
[Amit Varma]: But when you look at all these people who are submitting papers, people who are working

00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:18.600
[Amit Varma]: on the cutting edge of science, how does that come in? What is the level of humility you

00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:25.800
[Amit Varma]: think that we need? You know, is this a trap that people fall into, of not having adequate

00:53:25.800 --> 00:53:28.600
[Amit Varma]: humility? What's your take on this?

00:53:28.600 --> 00:53:36.680
[Guest]: I think scientists as a group, fill all sorts, you will find people who are absolutely humble

00:53:36.680 --> 00:53:42.280
[Guest]: and down to earth and will, and these are even Nobel Prize winners that you can approach

00:53:42.280 --> 00:53:46.960
[Guest]: them and you can talk to them and they will have coffee with you and they will discuss

00:53:46.960 --> 00:53:52.440
[Guest]: the science with you. And scientists in general, the one thing is they'll do love to talk about

00:53:52.440 --> 00:53:57.680
[Guest]: their work with anyone. I think that is basically the hook to if you're talking to anyone from

00:53:57.680 --> 00:54:02.840
[Guest]: someone starting off with their lab or someone who has won the Nobel Prize. If you just ask

00:54:02.840 --> 00:54:09.480
[Guest]: them what they do and why they do it, they can go on for a really long time. But there

00:54:09.480 --> 00:54:15.640
[Guest]: are people who are very good at, and at a certain extent, you are absolutely right.

00:54:15.640 --> 00:54:24.760
[Guest]: You have to play up the value of your work. And sometimes that is actually exaggerated.

00:54:24.760 --> 00:54:30.240
[Guest]: The thing is other scientists are, after a while, very good at picking up on those exaggerations.

00:54:30.240 --> 00:54:35.760
[Guest]: I don't think the public always is, and sometimes the press can even be taken for a ride. So

00:54:35.760 --> 00:54:41.880
[Guest]: I don't blame the press for this when a scientist said, well, and we see a lot of this in the

00:54:41.880 --> 00:54:48.960
[Guest]: media as well, when someone says, well, I have now created this molecule in my lab and

00:54:48.960 --> 00:54:55.800
[Guest]: it works really well against cancer cells. And so it gets, and they get taken in by that.

00:54:55.800 --> 00:55:04.520
[Guest]: But someone in the field would also know that the path to drugs is treacherous. Very few

00:55:04.520 --> 00:55:09.440
[Guest]: promising drugs actually make it down that path to actually become drugs that become

00:55:09.440 --> 00:55:16.000
[Guest]: approved and used in humans. And so some people are very, very good about exploiting that

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:23.160
[Guest]: and using that to their benefit. But you're right. So everyone has to do it to a certain

00:55:23.160 --> 00:55:28.400
[Guest]: extent. Complete humility doesn't get you anywhere. I mean, nobody knows what you're

00:55:28.400 --> 00:55:36.400
[Guest]: doing and there has to be a certain amount of excitement also conveyed to the audience.

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:42.880
[Guest]: And that has to come across both in the way that scientists speak, but also in the way

00:55:42.880 --> 00:55:49.640
[Guest]: that they write. Otherwise, it's just a collection of facts. And so they may seem like dry stories,

00:55:49.640 --> 00:55:55.040
[Guest]: but a lot of the research articles are actually presented in the form of a narrative. It's

00:55:55.040 --> 00:55:58.560
[Guest]: a different form of a narrative, but it is a narrative.

00:55:58.560 --> 00:56:04.120
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned the press and I'm reminded of this phrase that Michael Crichton coined

00:56:04.120 --> 00:56:08.840
[Amit Varma]: in honor of his friend Murray Gell-Mann, you know, is Gell-Mann amnesia, which basically

00:56:08.840 --> 00:56:13.920
[Amit Varma]: means that, you know, if you're the specialist in a field and you read something in a general

00:56:13.920 --> 00:56:18.440
[Amit Varma]: newspaper on your subject, you realize that is bullshit, that the guy just doesn't get

00:56:18.440 --> 00:56:23.400
[Amit Varma]: it. But when you read the rest of the newspaper, you take it as gospel because, hey, it's in

00:56:23.400 --> 00:56:28.720
[Amit Varma]: a big newspaper. Now, you know, journalists tend to be generalists and that's more true

00:56:28.720 --> 00:56:34.160
[Amit Varma]: today than ever, you know, Prem Panikkar in a recent episode with me spoke about how this

00:56:34.160 --> 00:56:39.600
[Amit Varma]: is one of the things where Indian journalism is just in a horrendous place that you have

00:56:39.600 --> 00:56:43.120
[Amit Varma]: cost cutting. It's always journalists who are let go. And if you have less journalists,

00:56:43.120 --> 00:56:48.160
[Amit Varma]: you have more journalists. If you have, sorry, if you have less journalists, you have more

00:56:48.160 --> 00:56:53.400
[Amit Varma]: generalists and you know, so your science beat reporter with a few notable exceptions

00:56:53.400 --> 00:57:01.240
[Amit Varma]: won't necessarily be someone who really gets it. And that can actually harm, you know,

00:57:01.240 --> 00:57:08.480
[Amit Varma]: how the people sort of understand science. So a dual question here. One is that, is this

00:57:08.480 --> 00:57:14.040
[Amit Varma]: a big problem and are there ways around it? And the other question is that what technology

00:57:14.040 --> 00:57:20.920
[Amit Varma]: has run in the last 20 years is that any specialist can go out there and put, you know, her views

00:57:20.920 --> 00:57:26.000
[Amit Varma]: out there. You can start a blog, you can start a newsletter, you can make YouTube videos,

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:30.280
[Amit Varma]: all the technology is within our reach. So you don't have these gatekeepers anymore,

00:57:30.280 --> 00:57:34.600
[Amit Varma]: anyone can communicate. Of course, the gatekeepers fulfill a useful function of being a filter

00:57:34.600 --> 00:57:40.400
[Amit Varma]: for quality. But you could argue that water finds its own level in any case. So, you know,

00:57:40.400 --> 00:57:45.600
[Amit Varma]: whether you're on YouTube or blogging, ultimately, the quality of your work will determine the

00:57:45.600 --> 00:57:50.720
[Amit Varma]: kind of credibility that you have. So there is this dual thing where, you know, journalism

00:57:50.720 --> 00:57:55.960
[Amit Varma]: and I find and I find that that this is inevitably true. Whenever I read journalism about a subject,

00:57:55.960 --> 00:58:02.280
[Amit Varma]: I know something about I am like WTF is this, you know, and but at the same time, what I

00:58:02.280 --> 00:58:09.560
[Amit Varma]: am heartened by is that a lot of people who are either specialists or are sort of passionate

00:58:09.560 --> 00:58:14.560
[Amit Varma]: about a subject are going out making their own content, all of that. So, you know, in

00:58:14.560 --> 00:58:19.120
[Amit Varma]: the broader context of bringing science to the people of sort of popularizing all of

00:58:19.120 --> 00:58:22.480
[Amit Varma]: this, what do you think? What's the ecosystem like? How is this playing out?

00:58:22.480 --> 00:58:29.520
[Guest]: This is a very good question. And I think I want to say that despite some of the challenges,

00:58:29.520 --> 00:58:35.800
[Guest]: many journalists during the pandemic, despite the constraints and the lack of information

00:58:35.800 --> 00:58:40.560
[Guest]: and knowledge, have done a tremendous job. And there are some Indian journalists as well

00:58:40.560 --> 00:58:47.200
[Guest]: who have even in the midst of even when the transparency hasn't been 100%, they have tried

00:58:47.200 --> 00:58:53.680
[Guest]: to get the best information. And so I do want to applaud them for for what they've done.

00:58:53.680 --> 00:58:59.520
[Guest]: As you mentioned, we all have our narrow focuses. And I can speak to what happens in in science

00:58:59.520 --> 00:59:04.500
[Guest]: and in science journalism. And I think the first thing that has to happen is that people

00:59:04.500 --> 00:59:09.960
[Guest]: need to be fine with with paying for good content. I mean, that's that's essentially

00:59:09.960 --> 00:59:17.680
[Guest]: where it starts. Good journalism takes time, it takes money, and it takes it's a person's

00:59:17.680 --> 00:59:23.360
[Guest]: profession. And so we have to be fine with paying for it. And then once we pay for it,

00:59:23.360 --> 00:59:28.800
[Guest]: we have to be fine with investing in those organizations. And in those journalists, I

00:59:28.800 --> 00:59:34.760
[Guest]: think if newsrooms are getting cut, and if newspapers are worried about about their science

00:59:34.760 --> 00:59:40.440
[Guest]: pages, then that's going to have an effect despite regardless of everything else, that's

00:59:40.440 --> 00:59:46.680
[Guest]: definitely going to have an effect. The other thing is that science takes time to get answers.

00:59:46.680 --> 00:59:50.960
[Guest]: And if sometimes if someone has a deadline that they have to get something out, that

00:59:50.960 --> 01:00:02.800
[Guest]: is 500, 600 words, by by 4pm, or 9pm, then it becomes very difficult to get a full story

01:00:02.800 --> 01:00:09.480
[Guest]: to be able to do that background reading and to get that research done. And so often what

01:00:09.480 --> 01:00:16.760
[Guest]: happens is that we see results that are presented uncritically without the broader picture,

01:00:16.760 --> 01:00:24.320
[Guest]: the broader framework of of what actually happened there. So often, it is just a rehash

01:00:24.320 --> 01:00:30.840
[Guest]: of the press release, and then a bunch of quotes from different people. And it's sort

01:00:30.840 --> 01:00:37.120
[Guest]: of this drip drip system of getting news out that doesn't put the picture in a bigger context.

01:00:37.120 --> 01:00:43.960
[Guest]: I would also say that journalists often strive for balance. And balance isn't always necessarily

01:00:43.960 --> 01:00:50.360
[Guest]: a necessarily a good thing if we're talking about topics like deforestation, or climate

01:00:50.360 --> 01:00:58.880
[Guest]: change or pollution, or, or air pollution, or groundwater being polluted. And you bring

01:00:58.880 --> 01:01:05.040
[Guest]: in all the scientists on one side, and then you bring in either the person who's polluting,

01:01:05.040 --> 01:01:12.120
[Guest]: or you bring in all the people who believe or have data that backs up climate change,

01:01:12.120 --> 01:01:17.280
[Guest]: anthropogenic climate change, and then you bring in industry interests on the other side.

01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:22.640
[Guest]: That's not balance. And so putting what happens is if you put both sets of quotes together,

01:01:22.640 --> 01:01:27.880
[Guest]: then it looks like that it's balanced. But I think journalists have to be reporters have

01:01:27.880 --> 01:01:34.040
[Guest]: to be fine with moving away from that sense of balance, with that sense of reporting everything

01:01:34.040 --> 01:01:42.160
[Guest]: as a as a short piece of something and trying to instead bring it into a framework of putting

01:01:42.160 --> 01:01:44.840
[Guest]: more context into it. But all of that requires money.

01:01:44.840 --> 01:01:49.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, there's that old thing that journalists say that, you know, if you're a journalist,

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:53.000
[Amit Varma]: and one person tells you it's raining, and the other person tells you it isn't raining,

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:56.360
[Amit Varma]: your job isn't to report both of them, it is to go to the window and report what you

01:01:56.360 --> 01:02:00.960
[Amit Varma]: see outside. And, you know, but this becomes difficult if you're a generalist, and you

01:02:00.960 --> 01:02:05.120
[Amit Varma]: have to turn in a piece by four o'clock, because you don't possibly have the base of knowledge

01:02:05.120 --> 01:02:10.600
[Amit Varma]: to be able to make those judgments yourself, which is why I think we kind of need more

01:02:10.600 --> 01:02:14.840
[Amit Varma]: specialists. You know, speaking of journalists, you know, the outliers who have done a great

01:02:14.840 --> 01:02:19.080
[Amit Varma]: job really stand out. I've loved the work of Zainab Tufekci, for example, during this

01:02:19.080 --> 01:02:24.880
[Amit Varma]: pandemic, I think some of her reporting has been outstanding. Before we actually get to

01:02:24.880 --> 01:02:31.680
[Amit Varma]: your book, a few, a couple of more sort of questions about, you know, your personal processes

01:02:31.680 --> 01:02:35.360
[Amit Varma]: and thinking and all of that. What do you do for knowledge management? Because you're

01:02:35.360 --> 01:02:39.600
[Amit Varma]: taking in a lot of information, especially for this book, you know, it's written in very

01:02:39.600 --> 01:02:44.920
[Amit Varma]: simple language, so it doesn't appear to, but it's packed with, you know, information

01:02:44.920 --> 01:02:48.960
[Amit Varma]: and insight. What do you do for knowledge management are the particular apps that you

01:02:48.960 --> 01:02:54.000
[Amit Varma]: use? And in general, this is surely something that even outside the context of this book,

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:57.760
[Amit Varma]: something that you must have kind of faced, you know, maybe in the context of productivity,

01:02:57.760 --> 01:03:03.600
[Amit Varma]: but even otherwise, you must be reading so much. Are there some hacks or tips or processes

01:03:03.600 --> 01:03:04.600
[Amit Varma]: that you've adopted?

01:03:04.600 --> 01:03:11.600
[Guest]: Yeah, I read a lot. And even though the book has a few hundred references, I read over

01:03:11.600 --> 01:03:19.040
[Guest]: 1000 papers, even just writing this book, 1000 scientific papers. And I would say, for

01:03:19.040 --> 01:03:25.920
[Guest]: a time, I was reading all the major stories in Indian Express, Washington Post and the

01:03:25.920 --> 01:03:31.720
[Guest]: New York Times, particularly during that lockdown phase, when there were a lot of reports coming

01:03:31.720 --> 01:03:39.640
[Guest]: out. And, and I use Mendeley, which is a reference manager. And so what it has is it has this

01:03:39.640 --> 01:03:47.040
[Guest]: web plugin, where when I go to the website of a publisher, scientific publisher, and

01:03:47.040 --> 01:03:53.400
[Guest]: I see that, that paper, I can click on the PDF, and it will immediately download that

01:03:53.400 --> 01:03:59.000
[Guest]: PDF and put it into the database. And then in the database, it's also a reference manager,

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:03.480
[Guest]: it has all the references there. So I can see all of those papers, and later I can I

01:04:03.480 --> 01:04:10.600
[Guest]: can read those, I read and annotate on my iPad. And I like to use the highlighter feature

01:04:10.600 --> 01:04:16.560
[Guest]: to do that as well. I still sometimes take for the for the actual outlines of the chapters,

01:04:16.560 --> 01:04:23.680
[Guest]: I use notebooks, I like to basically draw mind maps, and and do that, go through that

01:04:23.680 --> 01:04:31.240
[Guest]: process for for doing that as well. So I would say those are the the main ways that I, I

01:04:31.240 --> 01:04:37.960
[Guest]: decided, or I figured out how to do it. There are some really good accounts on Twitter that

01:04:37.960 --> 01:04:44.760
[Guest]: are a good source of information in terms of so I did bookmark a certain number of tweets

01:04:44.760 --> 01:04:52.800
[Guest]: of of people as well, to get some information. As far as my own Twitter account, I used it

01:04:52.800 --> 01:05:00.800
[Guest]: as as a test testing ground for seeing what people were interested in over the course

01:05:00.800 --> 01:05:05.900
[Guest]: of the year, they didn't know I was writing a book, I hadn't decided at that point either.

01:05:05.900 --> 01:05:12.800
[Guest]: But how I was framing things, whether that was useful or not. And I did a couple of of

01:05:12.800 --> 01:05:18.920
[Guest]: polls as well through the year, that definitely helped me out with that. One thing about the

01:05:18.920 --> 01:05:25.760
[Guest]: coronavirus pandemic, I'll say is that almost all scientific publishers made their coronavirus

01:05:25.760 --> 01:05:33.520
[Guest]: content free and outside of the paywall. And that was beneficial for someone like me. And

01:05:33.520 --> 01:05:37.640
[Guest]: this didn't this wasn't only with respect to the scientific publishers, I do subscribe

01:05:37.640 --> 01:05:44.600
[Guest]: to the New York Times and the Washington Post and Indian Express. But even they made the

01:05:44.600 --> 01:05:48.120
[Guest]: US publishers made their coronavirus content free.

01:05:48.120 --> 01:05:52.760
[Amit Varma]: Fabulous. And, you know, as this is still ongoing, and we're all searching for information,

01:05:52.760 --> 01:05:57.040
[Amit Varma]: are there are there sort of which are the Twitter handles you said that you follow that

01:05:57.040 --> 01:06:03.920
[Amit Varma]: you considered the best sources on this as it was unfolding? And also at a general level,

01:06:03.920 --> 01:06:08.560
[Amit Varma]: which are the best sources for understanding popular science, like in the context of economics,

01:06:08.560 --> 01:06:13.120
[Amit Varma]: for example, you have that great blog Marginal Revolution, which is, you know, done such

01:06:13.120 --> 01:06:21.140
[Amit Varma]: human service in, you know, popularizing the just the field in general. So let's say someone

01:06:21.140 --> 01:06:25.920
[Amit Varma]: is interested in science, they want to learn more about it. Like after my friend Ruben

01:06:25.920 --> 01:06:29.240
[Amit Varma]: Abraham told me about, you know, he sent me a bunch of science papers, which he's been

01:06:29.240 --> 01:06:35.240
[Amit Varma]: reading over the last few weeks, which he really likes, and I was kind of struck by

01:06:35.240 --> 01:06:40.000
[Amit Varma]: them. So let's say you're speaking to a layperson like me, I want to kind of know more about

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:44.560
[Amit Varma]: what's happening on the cutting edge of science, I want to know who to follow, and whose work

01:06:44.560 --> 01:06:49.240
[Amit Varma]: is interesting. And, you know, are there blogs, are there Twitter handles? How does someone

01:06:49.240 --> 01:06:51.920
[Amit Varma]: like me navigate this complex and messy field?

01:06:51.920 --> 01:06:58.080
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a good question. I will first answer the first part of that about the during the

01:06:58.080 --> 01:07:03.600
[Guest]: Coronavirus pandemic, certain people that I definitely would recommend following. One

01:07:03.600 --> 01:07:11.560
[Guest]: of them is at Eric Topol. So Dr. Eric Topol, who is at the Scripps Research Institute,

01:07:11.560 --> 01:07:18.200
[Guest]: and he is sort of a renaissance man of medicine. He is a cardiologist by training, but he's

01:07:18.200 --> 01:07:27.800
[Guest]: been on top of the Coronavirus pandemic. His, his work, his tweets are mainly covering the

01:07:27.800 --> 01:07:33.800
[Guest]: scientific articles. So some of it may be a little bit technical, but he covers all

01:07:33.800 --> 01:07:40.440
[Guest]: the major outlets, nature, science, cell, and some of the other journals as well. Whatever

01:07:40.440 --> 01:07:48.960
[Guest]: comes out, you will probably see some of the main conclusions in his, in his Twitter account,

01:07:48.960 --> 01:07:55.560
[Guest]: in his Twitter feed. I also follow Angie Rasmussen. She's moving to, she's a professor moving

01:07:55.560 --> 01:08:02.160
[Guest]: to Saskatchewan in Canada now. She's a fantastic virologist, but she also has a no nonsense

01:08:02.160 --> 01:08:09.480
[Guest]: way of presenting concepts in virology in a way that's very digestible to people. Natalie

01:08:09.480 --> 01:08:16.520
[Guest]: Dean is a professor in Florida, and she's a bio statistician. And that is very, very

01:08:16.520 --> 01:08:23.760
[Guest]: helpful to understand the statistical aspects and the mathematics beyond the, for example,

01:08:23.760 --> 01:08:29.080
[Guest]: the efficacy trials and herd immunity and things like that. Mark Lipsitch is a professor

01:08:29.080 --> 01:08:36.000
[Guest]: at Harvard Chan, and he is one of the leading epidemiologists who talked about the parameters

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:42.060
[Guest]: of the pandemic early on. Karl Bergstrom is at University of Washington. He's written

01:08:42.060 --> 01:08:48.000
[Guest]: this book called Calling Bullshit with Jevin West. And that is about misinformation and

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:54.300
[Guest]: dealing with, with misinformation. And his Twitter account is a source of a lot of great

01:08:54.300 --> 01:09:01.480
[Guest]: wisdom regarding misinformation during the pandemic. Adam Kucharski is at, is in the

01:09:01.480 --> 01:09:07.960
[Guest]: UK, I think at a School of Tropical Medicine, if I'm, if I'm not mistaken, and he has some

01:09:07.960 --> 01:09:12.880
[Guest]: really good work. He's written the Rules of Contagion, which is a book written before

01:09:12.880 --> 01:09:19.680
[Guest]: the pandemic, but it has some of the mathematical aspects of, of how to deal with pandemics

01:09:19.680 --> 01:09:27.200
[Guest]: and the parameters of that. And there are some other accounts as well. Ed Yong, obviously,

01:09:27.200 --> 01:09:33.560
[Guest]: Carl Zimmer, Helen Branswell, they are writing some absolutely top notch work as well. In

01:09:33.560 --> 01:09:40.480
[Guest]: terms of following the science as it is coming out, I would say there are some really good

01:09:40.480 --> 01:09:47.080
[Guest]: Twitter accounts. So there's a news account for Science Magazine and a news account for

01:09:47.080 --> 01:09:54.460
[Guest]: Nature. The news articles in Science and Nature are definitely geared towards more of a lay

01:09:54.460 --> 01:09:59.880
[Guest]: audience as opposed to the peer reviewed scientific research that gets published there. I also

01:09:59.880 --> 01:10:04.820
[Guest]: get the Nature newsletter every day. It's a very nice newsletter that has a roundup

01:10:04.820 --> 01:10:12.000
[Guest]: of all aspects of science in a very accessible manner, including, for example, the search

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:18.920
[Guest]: for life on, on Venus and the search for life on Mars and things like that. So it's, it

01:10:18.920 --> 01:10:25.320
[Guest]: gives a broader perspective of that. For those who are interested in biology, at a slightly

01:10:25.320 --> 01:10:31.760
[Guest]: deeper level, there is a magazine called The Scientist. And that covers a lot of in depth

01:10:31.760 --> 01:10:38.340
[Guest]: articles in science as well. So but I think following some Twitter accounts and then getting

01:10:38.340 --> 01:10:42.440
[Guest]: some newsletters is definitely very helpful in keeping up to date.

01:10:42.440 --> 01:10:47.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I'll put links to all of these in the show notes. And whichever ones of these

01:10:47.160 --> 01:10:51.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm familiar with, I agree with completely. In fact, talking about Eric Topol, I produced

01:10:51.480 --> 01:10:56.520
[Amit Varma]: a show also called Brave New World, which is an interview show hosted by Vasanth Dhar.

01:10:56.520 --> 01:11:00.880
[Amit Varma]: He had been a guest on the scene and the unseen a few weeks ago. And he does a show called

01:11:00.880 --> 01:11:05.240
[Amit Varma]: Brave New World. And we had Eric Topol as a guest on there. So, you know, so Vasanth

01:11:05.240 --> 01:11:09.600
[Amit Varma]: and Eric had a delightful conversation. This was episode four of Brave New World. The title

01:11:09.600 --> 01:11:15.440
[Amit Varma]: of the episode is Human and Artificial Intelligence in Healthcare. And Eric's book Deep Medicine

01:11:15.440 --> 01:11:19.080
[Amit Varma]: is also quite so eye opening in different ways, isn't it?

01:11:19.080 --> 01:11:25.360
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely. And this is the thing about Dr. Eric Topol that that absolutely amazes

01:11:25.360 --> 01:11:31.380
[Guest]: me is that he goes from one day talking about about wearables for preventing heart disease

01:11:31.380 --> 01:11:38.620
[Guest]: to the next day, having an opinion about on mass and an asymptomatic spread of COVID-19.

01:11:38.620 --> 01:11:43.880
[Guest]: So he has a deep and wide grasp of many aspects in medicine.

01:11:43.880 --> 01:11:48.240
[Amit Varma]: It's so incredible that it's now that we can have public intellectuals of this sort because

01:11:48.240 --> 01:11:53.040
[Amit Varma]: technology makes it so possible for them to get their voice out to sort of, you know,

01:11:53.040 --> 01:11:59.520
[Amit Varma]: build these sort of presences in people's lives using tech. So a couple of questions

01:11:59.520 --> 01:12:04.000
[Amit Varma]: while we are, you know, before we actually get take a break and get to your book, who

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:09.320
[Amit Varma]: were your influences when it comes to science writing? You know, like when you sort of start

01:12:09.320 --> 01:12:14.560
[Amit Varma]: thinking about the notion that science needs to be popularised that it cannot just be academics

01:12:14.560 --> 01:12:18.280
[Amit Varma]: talking to each other. When you think about writing your own book, is there something

01:12:18.280 --> 01:12:22.280
[Amit Varma]: that you're looking at as a model and saying, you know, this book nailed it or this is a

01:12:22.280 --> 01:12:27.960
[Amit Varma]: kind of voice that I want and so on. So what was sort of influences in that sense? And

01:12:27.960 --> 01:12:33.240
[Amit Varma]: they don't even have to be overt influences where, you know, you take a model from something

01:12:33.240 --> 01:12:37.720
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, but which are the science books that you have loved reading as you have grown

01:12:37.720 --> 01:12:41.960
[Amit Varma]: up? Or, you know, is there a book that kind of changed the way you think about the world

01:12:41.960 --> 01:12:45.400
[Amit Varma]: or that caused that moment where you know, a light bulb goes on in your head and you

01:12:45.400 --> 01:12:47.240
[Amit Varma]: see things differently?

01:12:47.240 --> 01:12:53.320
[Guest]: One of my favourite science writers definitely is Carl Sagan. And I've quoted him, and I

01:12:53.320 --> 01:13:02.440
[Guest]: admire him deeply. And his way of connecting and bringing the social passion, the passion

01:13:02.440 --> 01:13:08.720
[Guest]: for social justice into science and the broader picture is absolutely evident. And people,

01:13:08.720 --> 01:13:13.320
[Guest]: when they talk about Carl Sagan, they talk about Cosmos. But the Demon Haunted World

01:13:13.320 --> 01:13:19.360
[Guest]: is a much, much better and deeper book. Cosmos was a companion to a television show that

01:13:19.360 --> 01:13:24.640
[Guest]: was that I came out, I believe came out in 79 or 80, whereas the Demon Haunted World

01:13:24.640 --> 01:13:32.840
[Guest]: was much later and contained full length articles. So definitely, I like his work. I feel that

01:13:32.840 --> 01:13:39.560
[Guest]: the physicists do a much better job in general than the biologists in conveying maybe because

01:13:39.560 --> 01:13:44.520
[Guest]: their questions are grander on a grand on a much grander scale. So if you think about

01:13:44.520 --> 01:13:51.880
[Guest]: like Brian Greene or Michio Kaku or Jim Al-Khalili, who wrote what I thought was the best science

01:13:51.880 --> 01:13:57.040
[Guest]: book last year, which is The World According to Physics, has done a really, really good

01:13:57.040 --> 01:14:05.080
[Guest]: job with respect to that. I read voraciously. So I read last year, I read about 100 books,

01:14:05.080 --> 01:14:12.240
[Guest]: of which many of them were definitely science books. Michael Benton does a tremendous job

01:14:12.240 --> 01:14:17.760
[Guest]: in talking about dinosaurs. And I think that's a topic that a lot of people are interested

01:14:17.760 --> 01:14:26.880
[Guest]: in. So yeah, there are definitely a lot of people who do write well. In general, my observation

01:14:26.880 --> 01:14:31.960
[Guest]: is that the physicists do a much better job than the biologists.

01:14:31.960 --> 01:14:36.760
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating. And you know, you mentioned Sagan and I love this quote from your book

01:14:36.760 --> 01:14:41.480
[Amit Varma]: where you quote Sagan saying, quote, if you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you

01:14:41.480 --> 01:14:45.600
[Amit Varma]: must first invent the universe, stop quote, which is such a fantastic quote and which

01:14:45.600 --> 01:14:51.760
[Amit Varma]: applies to like just so many things, you know, it's beautiful. Now, my final question before

01:14:51.760 --> 01:14:57.520
[Amit Varma]: the break and before we get to both the delightful subject of your book and the difficult subject

01:14:57.520 --> 01:15:04.240
[Amit Varma]: of COVID-19, which is that through the process of writing this book, how have you changed?

01:15:04.240 --> 01:15:08.800
[Amit Varma]: How has it changed you as a person, as a writer, as someone who thinks about the world, you

01:15:08.800 --> 01:15:13.480
[Amit Varma]: know, because writing forces you not just to examine your subject that much more deeply,

01:15:13.480 --> 01:15:18.240
[Amit Varma]: it also forces you to examine yourself, you know, and especially in these difficult times,

01:15:18.240 --> 01:15:23.840
[Amit Varma]: I think there's a lot of self reflection everyone has kind of gone through, which for a writer

01:15:23.840 --> 01:15:28.280
[Amit Varma]: can become explicit, because sometimes they're writing about it, sometimes they're not, maybe

01:15:28.280 --> 01:15:33.120
[Amit Varma]: it's not even in the book, maybe it's in sort of the meditative tweets that you might put

01:15:33.120 --> 01:15:36.840
[Amit Varma]: out once in a while. But through this period, through the last few months, when you've written

01:15:36.840 --> 01:15:43.040
[Amit Varma]: this book, how have you kind of personally changed? How are you different from what you

01:15:43.040 --> 01:15:45.760
[Amit Varma]: were say, you know, 15 months ago?

01:15:45.760 --> 01:15:50.400
[Guest]: Yeah, I had never planned to write this book. This was I never thought that this would be

01:15:50.400 --> 01:15:55.760
[Guest]: my first book. If I thought that I would be writing something I had actually thought that

01:15:55.760 --> 01:16:03.960
[Guest]: I would be writing perhaps fiction or in Bangla or meditative essays about about travel or

01:16:03.960 --> 01:16:08.800
[Guest]: cooking or something of that nature. But when the pandemic struck, I felt and people were

01:16:08.800 --> 01:16:13.720
[Guest]: asking me all these questions, I felt that there was because of my experience, I had

01:16:13.720 --> 01:16:19.080
[Guest]: at least something that I could offer. And so I felt that it was a sense of obligation

01:16:19.080 --> 01:16:26.040
[Guest]: that I had to write this. It was a very humbling experience, the entire pandemic, but the course

01:16:26.040 --> 01:16:36.320
[Guest]: of writing. And, and I will say that I am now more attuned to myself and more. I think

01:16:36.320 --> 01:16:42.160
[Guest]: I'm fine with saying I don't know, and I'm fine with more uncertainty now. I was more

01:16:42.160 --> 01:16:49.200
[Guest]: certain about certain things at the start of the pandemic. And as and moving forward,

01:16:49.200 --> 01:16:55.600
[Guest]: that has changed. I had started with the idea of writing a book that would be a mainly a

01:16:55.600 --> 01:17:02.280
[Guest]: scientific book, but very early on, it became evident that that the science alone was not

01:17:02.280 --> 01:17:08.640
[Guest]: going to determine the outcome of this pandemic, it's not going to determine the outcome of

01:17:08.640 --> 01:17:15.960
[Guest]: any aspect of the major challenges that humans face today, including climate change or deforestation

01:17:15.960 --> 01:17:22.200
[Guest]: or antimicrobial resistance. Science is probably one of the easier pieces. I mean, if we look

01:17:22.200 --> 01:17:27.920
[Guest]: at the scientists worked hard, they got the vaccines created in time. But that is just

01:17:27.920 --> 01:17:37.000
[Guest]: a small piece of of the larger tapestry of society and all the the the components that

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:45.360
[Guest]: go into this pandemic. And the other realization was that every single source of inequality

01:17:45.360 --> 01:17:51.960
[Guest]: or of injustice that we had in our society was magnified during the pandemic. We like

01:17:51.960 --> 01:17:57.440
[Guest]: to say that, okay, we are all in this together. I do not believe that now having gone through

01:17:57.440 --> 01:18:03.840
[Guest]: this, we are not all in it together in the same way for someone like me, who was privileged

01:18:03.840 --> 01:18:09.440
[Guest]: and I did get a sense of my own privilege of being able to actually stay at home and

01:18:09.440 --> 01:18:14.520
[Guest]: write a book during a pandemic. I mean, that's immense privilege. And someone else who is

01:18:14.520 --> 01:18:21.120
[Guest]: basically having a difficult time making his or her living. That is that is definitely

01:18:21.120 --> 01:18:26.320
[Guest]: something that got magnified. And the other pieces of I mentioned some of these things

01:18:26.320 --> 01:18:30.840
[Guest]: in the book is that we tell people to wash their hands. But how can we tell someone who

01:18:30.840 --> 01:18:35.560
[Guest]: doesn't have clean water how to wash their hands with soap? How can we tell someone who

01:18:35.560 --> 01:18:41.920
[Guest]: lives in the slums to socially distance? So we have to make our society more equitable.

01:18:41.920 --> 01:18:49.480
[Guest]: And that was for me, one of the other observations. And then finally, a lot of the things that

01:18:49.480 --> 01:18:57.640
[Guest]: I saw that I feared would happen, and they did happen because of this, this sense of

01:18:57.640 --> 01:19:03.760
[Guest]: mistrust in science and this, this society that where we have built where experts are

01:19:03.760 --> 01:19:09.440
[Guest]: often vilified. And this happened to a great extent in the United States where I currently

01:19:09.440 --> 01:19:15.320
[Guest]: live. But it happened elsewhere as well, where we were the science was way ahead of what

01:19:15.320 --> 01:19:21.080
[Guest]: people were doing. But people were still dying because they were not taking simple measures.

01:19:21.080 --> 01:19:27.040
[Guest]: I mean, wearing a mask became an ideological issue. That should be a public health matter.

01:19:27.040 --> 01:19:31.600
[Guest]: And we can go on and on about that. But I think overall, it was a very, very humbling

01:19:31.600 --> 01:19:38.560
[Guest]: experience for me to see that and to see the disparities. I mentioned a couple of examples

01:19:38.560 --> 01:19:45.120
[Guest]: in the book. One of them is in the part on the impact where I was talking about a large

01:19:45.120 --> 01:19:52.440
[Guest]: fraction of the world is not going to get basic immunizations for diseases like measles.

01:19:52.440 --> 01:19:57.560
[Guest]: And on the other hand, there are privileged people in other parts of the world who are

01:19:57.560 --> 01:20:03.720
[Guest]: using zoom and they don't like how they look on zoom. And they're going for plastic surgery.

01:20:03.720 --> 01:20:08.480
[Guest]: So just by putting these two facts together, you can see the dichotomy in society. Or even

01:20:08.480 --> 01:20:14.120
[Guest]: during the lockdown, we had people who travel for miles and they didn't even have any food,

01:20:14.120 --> 01:20:19.440
[Guest]: they had nothing to eat. And on the other hand, we there are people who are surreptitiously

01:20:19.440 --> 01:20:25.560
[Guest]: getting onto golf courses because they needed to get their 18 holes of golf in during the

01:20:25.560 --> 01:20:33.200
[Guest]: pandemic. And so, yeah, it's just the scale of this was, was perhaps you don't see that

01:20:33.200 --> 01:20:39.040
[Guest]: outside of a pandemic. But definitely it brought into sharp relief the divisions that we have

01:20:39.040 --> 01:20:44.560
[Guest]: in our society. So it started off as a science book, it definitely didn't end that way. And

01:20:44.560 --> 01:20:47.680
[Guest]: it's definitely changed me as well through the process of writing this.

01:20:47.680 --> 01:20:51.640
[Amit Varma]: Wow, that's so fascinating. And I didn't know that people are getting plastic surgery, because

01:20:51.640 --> 01:20:57.080
[Amit Varma]: of zoom. Like, you know, I haven't got a haircut in months, as you can see, but thankfully,

01:20:57.080 --> 01:21:00.480
[Unknown]: the podcast is not a video thing. And that's something I've kind of been reflecting on

01:21:00.480 --> 01:21:06.600
[Amit Varma]: as well. Like I've been extraordinarily fortunate during this pandemic to be able to do the

01:21:06.600 --> 01:21:10.160
[Amit Varma]: things that I do to be able to you know, I've worked from home for 12-13 years. So it's

01:21:10.160 --> 01:21:15.400
[Amit Varma]: not a big deal. Just shoot up my laptop, do what I do, it's completely okay. But especially

01:21:15.400 --> 01:21:19.480
[Amit Varma]: in India, these differences are so stark. If you look at what happened to the migrant

01:21:19.480 --> 01:21:23.800
[Amit Varma]: laborers, you know, they used to be stories during the partition that when trains from

01:21:23.800 --> 01:21:28.600
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan would come into India, or vice versa, trains from India would go there, you know,

01:21:28.600 --> 01:21:33.280
[Amit Varma]: the train would reach the final destination with everyone inside it dead because they

01:21:33.280 --> 01:21:38.920
[Amit Varma]: had been killed. And I did an episode with Ruben Mascarenas on, you know, who did a lot

01:21:38.920 --> 01:21:44.640
[Amit Varma]: of work feeding hungry people during the pandemic in Mumbai. And he spoke about how, you know,

01:21:44.640 --> 01:21:47.440
[Amit Varma]: there were actually trains where they would put a migrant worker on a train and they would

01:21:47.440 --> 01:21:52.280
[Amit Varma]: feed them in Mumbai, but everywhere else there's no one feeding them. And three days later,

01:21:52.280 --> 01:21:56.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, the guy stumbles out on the platform wherever he is in his hometown and just dies,

01:21:56.320 --> 01:22:02.280
[Amit Varma]: dies of starvation in in like the 21st century. So that's, that's just completely nuts. We

01:22:02.280 --> 01:22:06.480
[Amit Varma]: will, of course, discuss a little bit more about the politics of it after the break.

01:22:06.480 --> 01:22:11.960
[Amit Varma]: The other thing that I think the pandemic really made stark, especially in an Indian

01:22:11.960 --> 01:22:18.520
[Amit Varma]: context is how dysfunctional our state is. The various ways, I mean, the state fundamentally

01:22:18.520 --> 01:22:23.440
[Amit Varma]: in India, I've always said there is no rule of law for most people. The state is absent,

01:22:23.440 --> 01:22:26.880
[Amit Varma]: it doesn't do any of the things that it should do properly and does a lot of things that

01:22:26.880 --> 01:22:33.080
[Amit Varma]: it should not do at all. And we've seen an exacerbation of this. Like it's just coming

01:22:33.080 --> 01:22:38.120
[Amit Varma]: to stark relief through the last few months. I've written a column on this, which I linked

01:22:38.120 --> 01:22:44.000
[Amit Varma]: from the show notes. But it's kind of distressing that, you know, that in a sense, in this terrible

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:48.920
[Amit Varma]: tragedy, at least there are some things that we should be able to see more clearly, which

01:22:48.920 --> 01:22:55.880
[Amit Varma]: should not immediately get normalized as this gets over. And these are these thoughts are

01:22:55.880 --> 01:23:01.960
[Amit Varma]: too deep, we have to take a break. So we'll take a break and come back in a minute.

01:23:01.960 --> 01:23:06.840
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer. In fact, chances are that many of you first

01:23:06.840 --> 01:23:12.600
[Amit Varma]: heard of me because of my blog India Uncut, which was active between 2003 and 2009, and

01:23:12.600 --> 01:23:17.240
[Amit Varma]: became somewhat popular at the time. I love the freedom the form gave me. And I feel I

01:23:17.240 --> 01:23:22.880
[Amit Varma]: was shaped by it in many ways. I exercise my writing muscle every day, and was forced

01:23:22.880 --> 01:23:27.360
[Amit Varma]: to think about many different things because I wrote about many different things. Well,

01:23:27.360 --> 01:23:32.480
[Amit Varma]: that phase in my life ended for various reasons. And now it is time to revive it. Only now

01:23:32.480 --> 01:23:37.320
[Amit Varma]: I'm doing it through a newsletter. I have started the India Uncut newsletter at India

01:23:37.320 --> 01:23:43.560
